hi, i&#39;m making a multi-agent sim thingy where i&#39;m hoping to evolve
agents 
that can play tag -- although i seem to remember seeing a paper about
this 
somewhere, but i&#39;m enjoying doing it on my own.

the basic idea is to have a finite size area, agents with 
position/velocity, and at any one time, an &quot;it&quot; - which can change if
the 
current It touches another. I figure that this would be an interesting 
thing to learn, since when an agent is not It they will be trying to run
away from It, and when they are It they will try to run towards another 
agent. i want to use competitive co-evolution and NN controllers 
(eventually using neat, although i&#39;m using a simple crossover+mutation
GA 
with binary tournament selection right now). fitness is the average 
distance from the target over a certain number of time steps.

my first task was just for agents to follow around a moving target,
where 
their input is a bearing to the target and their outputs is a change to 
their current x and y velocities - this is basically evolving sin and 
cosine in the network. with a population size of 10, with 5 new
offspring 
each turn, it readily solves this problem within a couple hundred 
generations. even though ive done all sorts of evolutionary algorithms, 
its still DAMN cool to see the little dots start out moving randomly and
then over time start swarming around the target ... hehe this stuff is
so 
cool. anyway, i then changed their output to be their new heading and 
velocity, and they also learn how to follow the target fairly easily, 
although now that i think about it since one of the inputs is the
bearing 
they pretty much just need to learn to turn to the bearing.

anyway, my question is this: what do you use as inputs for something 
like the tag 
problem? i mean 
i guess 
technically i could have an input which gives the bearing for each other
agent and then a binary input whether or not they are It. i don&#39;t really
like this, though, because you have to change the number of inputs based
on the current number of agents in the simulation. other ideas ive had 
were to divide the circle around the agent into a discrete number of
arcs 
and then flag the inputs that have something in their field of vision
... 
has anyone tried anything with that kind of thing?

--

a separate question, what is the best solution for a light-weight,
drop-in 
with as little change as possible c++ implementation of neat? hehe no 
offense, 
Ken, but i saw your code a few years ago - hope you cleaned it up since 
then :) if there isn&#39;t an existing implementation that has a very clean 
interface, are there any plans to develop one?

anyway, i really should be studying for my exams, but i&#39;ve convinced 
myself that this really is revision -- which, actually, it is, since 
monday&#39;s exam is neural computation and tuesday&#39;s is nature inspired 
design, so i&#39;m actually using concepts from both of those classes in
this 
little system.

cheers,
-KB-

